solution.p:
	Substituting the known value for sine into the Pythagorean identity, we have

	 \cos^2(\theta) + \left(\frac{3}{7}\right)^2 \amp= 1 \amp\amp \text{Simplifying}
	 
	 \cos^2(\theta) + \frac{9}{49} \amp= 1 \amp\amp \text{Subtracting } \frac{9}{49} \text{ from both sides}
	 
	 \cos^2(\theta) \amp= \frac{40}{49} \amp\amp \text{Taking the square root of both sides }
	 
	 \cos(\theta) \amp= \pm \sqrt{\frac{40}{49}} \amp\amp \text{Simplifying} 
	 
	 \amp= \pm \frac{\sqrt{40}}{7} 
	 
	 \amp= \pm \frac{2\sqrt{10}}{7}
